      <hedline>
        <hl1>An Election Equation: Nader and the X Factor</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Susan Gellman letter praises Ralph Nader's campaign for bringing important issues to forefront, but urges him now to throw support to Al Gore (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Democrats Hear Thunder on Left, and Try to Steal Some of Nader's'' (front page, Oct. 25):</p>
        <p>I'm glad that Ralph Nader decided to run for president. As always, he brought important issues to the forefront, and the major parties had to address them. Mr. Nader makes sure that inconvenient truths cannot be ignored.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Democrats Hear Thunder on Left, and Try to Steal Some of Nader's'' (front page, Oct. 25):</p>
        <p>I'm glad that Ralph Nader decided to run for president. As always, he brought important issues to the forefront, and the major parties had to address them. Mr. Nader makes sure that inconvenient truths cannot be ignored.</p>
        <p>But he's accomplished that. And now that the race is so tight, it is unfortunately true that a vote for Mr. Nader is a vote for George W. Bush.  Many Nader supporters would welcome a green light from their candidate to vote pragmatically under these circumstances.</p>
        <p>The Nader campaign is a success  because it reached its goals of education and enlightenment. For Mr. Nader to give Al Gore his support would be further success, not surrender.</p>
        <p>SUSAN GELLMAN  Columbus, Ohio, Oct. 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
